article.description:
Betty Lennox scored 24 points and Lauren Jackson
had 17 points and 12 rebounds, leading the defending WNBA champion Seattle Storm to a 79-69 come-from-behind victory over the visiting Houston
Comets on Friday night.
article.headline: Lennox, Jackson lead charge for Storm
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- The pressure of not playing like the defending
WNBA champs was weighing heavily on the Seattle Storm at halftime.

"We got mired in the pressure and in the second half, we let it
go," Storm coach Anne Donovan said. "It's a natural tendency. You
get tight when things don't go well."

Betty Lennox scored 24 points and Lauren Jackson had 17 points
and 12 rebounds, leading the Storm to a 79-69 come-from-behind
victory over the Houston Comets on Friday night.

The Storm, who lost to Los Angeles at home by 18 points in their
opener last Saturday, trailed Houston by 14 points at halftime.
Seattle then outscored the Comets 53-29 in the second half, when it
shot 75 percent (18-for-24).

In contrast, the Storm shot a franchise-worst 23.7 percent
(18-for-76) in their opener.

The 6-foot-5 Jackson, a three-time WNBA All-Star and the league
MVP in 2003, had 12 points and eight rebounds in the second half,
while Lennox scored 18 points.

"With four minutes left in the first half, we talked about
Lauren having just one shot in the first half," Donovan said. "We
needed to get the ball to her inside."

Jackson said it was a matter of the Storm playing with much more
passion in the second half.

"We played with heart," she said.

Jackson lauded the performance of Lennox.

"She was unbelievable," Jackson said. "She made some amazing
shots. She was just wonderful. She's going to have a very big
year."

Sue Bird credited her coach with motivating the Storm with some
strong words at halftime.

"Anne came in here and woke us up," Bird said. "We needed
that. We can't worry about if we're going to win or we're going to
lose. Just play and have fun. We did that in the second half and
you saw the result."

Michelle Snow had 17 points and Sheryl Swoopes added 16 for the
Comets, who lost for the first time in three games.

Comets coach Van Chancellor said his team knew Seattle was
capable of coming back, but couldn't seem to do anything about it.

"We talked about it and how we needed to play better in the
second half, but we just didn't." he said. "I thought Seattle
came out in the second half and really brought it. They showed a
lot more intensity and played really, really well."

The Storm scored the first 10 points of the second half, taking
the lead 47-46 on an offensive rebound by Janell Burse 7:44 into
the half.

The Comets went back in front 56-50 with 7:25 to go after a
12-foot bank shot by Swoopes, but the Storm went on an 11-0 run.

Houston cut its deficit to 61-58 on a basket by Snow, but Lennox
hit a 12-footer, Iziane Castro Marques made three free throws after
being fouled by Swoopes on a 3-point attempt, and Bird made a short
jumper with 3:16 left to put the Storm in front 68-58.

The Comets led 40-26 at halftime, holding Jackson to five points
on 2-for-5 shooting. Jackson didn't get her first basket until 2:50
was left in the opening quarter, when she scored on a putback after
missing her first three shots.

Snow and Swoopes each scored 10 points in the opening half, with
Snow shooting 5-for-7 and Swoopes 5-for-9. Houston shot 18-for-30
in the first half.

Swoopes, 34, who played 37 minutes, looked tired in the second
half, when she shot 2-for-7.

"I kind of felt we beat ourselves," she said. "You don't have
a 14-point lead against a good team like that and give the game
away in the second half. I think that's what we did."
